17
00:02:05,440 --> 00:02:09,360
Let's get started. Bitcoin is digital money.

18
00:02:09,360 --> 00:02:14,300
Euros and dollars are also digital, but 
bitcoin is not owned by a government.

19
00:02:14,300 --> 00:02:25,520
You can send it from anywhere in the world,
near instantaneously, securely, and for minimal fees.

20
00:02:25,520 --> 00:02:30,460
Two days ago, we saw one of the largest transactions
ever recorded on the Bitcoin network.

21
00:02:30,460 --> 00:02:42,280
Someone transferred $150 million [worth 
of bitcoin] in [about ten minutes], for zero fees.

22
00:02:42,280 --> 00:02:52,980
That should allow you to grasp how disruptive this
will be, in terms of international payment systems.

23
00:02:52,980 --> 00:02:56,120
But this is just the beginning.

24
00:02:56,120 --> 00:03:04,420
Bitcoin is a digital currency that was invented
in 2008 by a person called Satoshi Nakamoto.

25
00:03:04,420 --> 00:03:11,840
He published a paper where he posited that he
had found a way to create a decentralized network,

26
00:03:11,840 --> 00:03:18,960
that could achieve consensus / agreement 
without any central controlling authority.

27
00:03:18,960 --> 00:03:25,640
If you study computer science or distributed systems,
this is known as the Byzantine Generals' Problem.

28
00:03:25,640 --> 00:03:31,720
It was first described in [1982].
Until 2008, it was an unsolved problem.

29
00:03:31,720 --> 00:03:39,360
But we understood the importance of solving it.
Satoshi Nakamoto said that he had solved it.

30
00:03:39,360 --> 00:03:45,820
Guess what happened next? Everybody laughed.
Many ignored and dismissed him.

31
00:03:45,820 --> 00:03:55,500
He published the whitepaper. Three months later,
he published the software to start the Bitcoin network.

32
00:03:55,500 --> 00:04:05,640
Bitcoin is not a company or organization.
It is a standard protocol, just like TCP/IP for the internet.

33
00:04:05,640 --> 00:04:10,460
It is not owned by anyone [single entity].
It operates based on mathematical rules.

34
00:04:10,460 --> 00:04:14,000
Everyone who participates in
the network must agree on them.

35
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:25,820
Bitcoin is a decentralized network of computers that,
through this consensus mechanism, agree on...

36
00:04:25,820 --> 00:04:34,040
what transactions have occurred on the network,
and who currently owns what money.

37
00:04:34,040 --> 00:04:44,120
If I send money to somebody else's "account"
in this peer-to-peer network, like sending email,

38
00:04:44,120 --> 00:04:45,480
there is no one in the middle.

39
00:04:45,480 --> 00:04:50,800
[The bitcoin transaction is broadcast] from
my computer to the recipient's computer,

40
00:04:50,800 --> 00:04:52,920
without intervention.

41
00:04:52,920 --> 00:04:58,220
Every ten minutes, the network agrees
on what transactions have happened,

42
00:04:58,220 --> 00:05:04,220
without any centralized authority,
a kind of election that occurs electronically.

43
00:05:04,220 --> 00:05:09,280
This particular solution [to the Byzantine Generals'
Problem] is far more important than currency.

44
00:05:09,280 --> 00:05:16,480
Currency is just the first application that you
can build on a distributed consensus system.

45
00:05:16,480 --> 00:05:27,040
Other applications include voting, stock ownership,
asset registration, notarization, and many others.

46
00:05:27,040 --> 00:05:33,820
Applications we have never thought of before.
I discovered Bitcoin for the first time in 2011.

47
00:05:33,820 --> 00:05:36,740
Since [the early days of] the internet,

48
00:05:36,740 --> 00:05:42,820
I have not felt this feeling of being completely
overwhelmed by the possibilities I saw.

49
00:05:42,820 --> 00:05:47,940
I was there at the dawn of the internet
in 1991, when it was pre-commercial.

50
00:05:47,940 --> 00:05:53,840
